e="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gfinc"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdtcsh"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcorrp"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gmurd"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdtcsh"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdtcsh"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpex"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Executive News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gdtcsh"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipcre">US </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World news</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Banker at center of Malta corruption scandal charged with money laundering</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>An Iranian banker was arrested in the US on charges that he participated in a money-laundering scheme in violations of US sanctions</Para><Para>An Iranian banker at the centre of a corruption scandal in Malta that was closely followed by the <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://viewer.gutools.co.uk/world/2017/oct/16/malta-car-bomb-kills-panama-papers-journalist">murdered journalist Daphne Caruana Galizia</ELink> has been arrested in the US on charges of money laundering and sanctions busting.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Ali Sadr, an Iranian who resides in Washington DC and is the owner of Pilatus Bank in Malta, was arrested and charged in a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/iranian-national-arrested-scheme-evade-us-economic-sanctions-illicitly-sending-more-115">six-count indictment</ELink> that alleged he participated in a scheme to illegally funnel $115m in payments from Venezuela to Iranian individuals, in violation of US sanctions and anti-money laundering rules.</Para><Para>The criminal charges raise significant new questions about the future operations of Sadrâs private bank in Malta, which an investigation by Maltese authorities showed caters to at least one Maltese public official and members of Azerbaijanâs ruling family. The investigation was initiated in 2013, authorities said.</Para><Para>Pilatus opened a branch in Mayfair, London, in 2017, under European âpassportingâ rules that allow a bank to open multiple branches with reduced anti-money laundering checks after it has been established in one EU country.</Para><Para>The development also poses questions about how Sadr, who is the son of one of Iranâs richest men, came to win â and keep â a banking license in the Mediterranean country.</Para><Para>The bank was the subject of a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://viewer.gutools.co.uk/world/2017/oct/17/the-situation-is-desperate-murdered-maltese-journalists-daphne-caruana-galizia-final-words">detailed investigation by Maltaâs anti-money laundering agency</ELink>, the FIAU, in 2016. The FIAU alleged in a report that the bank showed a âglaring, possibly deliberate disregardâ for money-laundering controls. Pilatus has said in the past that it denies any wrongdoing and fully adheres to all laws and regulations.</Para><Para>Asked about Sadrâs indictment, a senior Maltese banking regulator who spoke to the Guardian on the condition of anonymity said that âfitness and propernessâ were important considerations in determining whether a bank could maintain a banking license in the wake of Sadrâs indictment.</Para><Para>Pilatus did not respond to a request for comment. The bank was not named in the criminal indictment and has not been accused of wrongdoing by US authorities.</Para><Para>But the charges against Sadr have bolstered critics of the bank.</Para><Para>David Casa, a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.facebook.com/DavidCasaMEP/">Maltese MEP</ELink> who is a frequent critic of Maltese prime minister Joseph Muscat, said in a letter to the chairperson of the European Banking Authority, that the indictment called for a further investigation into Pilatus.</Para><Para>He also called on the EBA to examine whether Maltaâs chief banking regulator, the MFSA, was aware of Sadrâs alleged criminal activity and whether the decision to grant the bank a banking licence was the result of favourable political interference by an official within the Muscat government.</Para><Para>Related: <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/nov/15/eu-raises-serious-concerns-over-rule-of-law-in-malta-daphne-caruana-galizia">"Serious concern" over rule of law in Malta after murder of journalist</ELink></Para><Para>He pointed to an allegation by the FIAU that Keith Schembri, Muscatâs controversial chief of staff, had received questionable payments, which originated from Russian nationals, into a Pilatus account that was held in Schembriâs name.</Para><Para>Schembri has said the payments were a legitimate repayment of debts from a friend and has denied wrongdoing.</Para><Para>Caruana Galizia, who was killed in a car bomb in October, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/02/daphne-caruana-galizia-was-being-sued-defamation-at-time-of-her-murder">was being sued by Pilatus</ELink> for defamation and for causing damage to the bankâs reputation at the time of death. The <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://viewer.gutools.co.uk/world/2018/feb/22/meps-call-for-power-to-tackle-vexatious-lawsuits-targeting-journalists">lawsuit was later</ELink> dropped.</Para><Para>Caruana Galizia had made a wide range of enemies, reporting on a political system rife with corruption, businesses seemingly used to launder money or pay bribes, and a criminal justice system that seemed incapable, or unwilling, to take on the controlling minds behind it all.</Para><Para>Caruana Galiziaâs three sons â Matthew, Paul, and Andrew â welcomed the news that criminal charges would be considered by a court.</Para><Para>âWe wish our mother could have been alive to see it happen,â the brothers said.</Para><Para>The US case against Sadr was brought by the US Department of Justice and by local law enforcement office in the district attorneyâs office in Manhattan.</Para><Para>In court documents, prosecutors have alleged that Sadr â who is referred to as Ali Sadr Hashemi Nejad â skimmed $115m of a nearly $500m Venezuelan construction contract through the US banking system. He is alleged to have used a vast network of front companies and foreign bank accounts to mask Iranâs business dealings in Venezuela, and then used entities in Switzerland, Turkey, and British Virgin Islands to funnel the funds back to Iran.</Para><Para>âSadrâs arrest and the FBIâs investigation into his actions are further evidence of Iranâs never-ending attempts to circumvent US sanctions. It also illustrates the FBI New Yorkâs relentless pursuit of actors representing the Iranian government, and our success at thwarting the use of the US banking systems for Iranâs nefarious goals,â said assistant director-in-charge William Sweeney.</Para><Para>The court records alleged that a business owned by an Iranian conglomerate called Stratus Group, which was controlled by Sadrâs family, entered into a multi-million dollar arrangement with the Venezuelan government in 2004 in which they agreed to an infrastructure project to build thousands of homes in Venezuela.</Para><Para>According to prosecutors, Sadr took steps to hide the role of Iranian parties in the transaction as he funneled proceeds from the contract through the US banking system.</Para><Para>In one case, Sadr and an unnamed co-conspirator used passports they acquired in St Kitts and Nevis and an address in the UAE to incorporate two entities outside Iran to receive the dollar payments.</Para><Para>It is alleged that one entity, called Clarity Trade and Finance, was incorporated in Switzerland, while another, Stratus International Contracting, was incorporated in Turkey.</Para><Para>The two entities were used to funnel the dollar payments to an offshore entity in the British Virgin Islands. Clarity also wired $2m in proceeds from the Venezuelan project back into the US, where it was used to purchase real estate in California.</Para><Para>The justice department said that the case was being handled by the terrorism and international narcotics unit.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Stephanie Kirchgaessner and Juliette Garside </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Â© Copyright 2018.  The Guardian.  All rights reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:arc